{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778987509390,"sessionID":"ses_1cc17fd5bffeQIGMKJLRwjtTA3","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_0wE2BcF6IIWFrv8BlaXgmbWS","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+## PMID:32024243 \"Inflammatory Reaction Induced by Two Metalloproteinases Isolated from Bothrops atrox Venom and by Fragments Generated from the Hydrolysis of Basement Membrane Components.\"\n+\n+Review of the abstract shows direct support for a venom-mediated inflammatory response term and for child terms capturing edema, leukocyte infiltration, and release of inflammatory mediators. The paper reports that Bothrops atrox metalloproteinases induce edema, leukocyte accumulation, and TNF-alpha release.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32024243 \"Both SVMPs induced edema, representing an increase of ~70% of the paw size. Leukocyte infiltrates reached levels of 6 × 106 with ATXL and 5 × 106 with BATXH. TNF-α was identified in the supernatant of BATXH-or venom-stimulated MPAC cells.\"\n+    - Supports venom-mediated inflammatory response as a broader parent process.\n+    - Supports venom-mediated leukocyte infiltration.\n+    - Supports venom-mediated release of inflammatory mediator.\n+\n+## PMID:19000915 \"BthMP: a new weakly hemorrhagic metalloproteinase from Bothrops moojeni snake venom.\"\n+\n+The abstract supports that a snake venom metalloproteinase contributes to inflammatory activity, edema, and leukocytic infiltrate in vivo.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:19000915 \"The edema evidenced the important role of the toxin in the inflammatory activity of the venom. BthMP also caused unclotting, and provoked histological alterations in the gastrocnemius muscle of mice inducing hemorrhage, necrosis and leukocytic infiltrate.\"\n+    - Supports venom-mediated inflammatory response.\n+    - Supports venom-mediated leukocyte infiltration.\n+\n+## PMID:26072684 \"Inflammatory mediators involved in the paw edema and hyperalgesia induced by Batroxase, a metalloproteinase isolated from Bothrops atrox snake venom.\"\n+\n+The abstract supports that inflammatory mediators, including histamine and leukotrienes, are involved in the edema response induced by venom metalloproteinase, and that mast cell degranulation contributes to this response.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26072684 \"Our results indicate a major involvement of histamine and leukotrienes in the edema and hyperalgesia induced by Batroxase, which could be related, at least in part, to mast cell degranulation.\"\n+    - Supports venom-mediated release of inflammatory mediator.\n+    - Supports adding venom-mediated mast cell degranulation as part_of venom-mediated inflammatory response.\n*** Add File: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+## Relevant design-pattern review for issue #31902\n+\n+No dedicated DOSDP pattern was found for venom-mediated inflammatory outcome terms under `src/patterns`.\n+\n+Existing ontology precedent in `go-edit.obo` shows two modeling styles relevant here:\n+\n+1. Venom-mediated perturbation terms that directly regulate a host GO process often use `intersection_of` with `regulates_in_another_organism`, `positively_regulates_in_another_organism`, or `negatively_regulates_in_another_organism`.\n+2. Phenotypic or outcome-like venom terms such as `GO:0044398 venom-mediated edema`, `GO:0044521 venom-mediated muscle damage in another organism`, and `GO:0044536 venom-mediated depletion of circulating fibrinogen` are modeled more conservatively using asserted `is_a` parents and, where helpful, additional `relationship: part_of` links.\n+\n+For this issue, the conservative pattern is the better fit:\n+\n+- `venom-mediated inflammatory response` is modeled as an asserted subclass of `GO:0035738 venom-mediated perturbation of biological process`.\n+- `venom-mediated leukocyte infiltration` is modeled as an asserted subclass of the new inflammatory-response term, with an additional `part_of GO:0006954 ! inflammatory response` relationship to align it with the general inflammatory process.\n+- `venom-mediated release of inflammatory mediator` is modeled as an asserted subclass of the new inflammatory-response term without a new equivalence axiom, because \"inflammatory mediator\" spans multiple molecular entities and release processes.\n+- `GO:0044480 venom-mediated mast cell degranulation` receives `relationship: part_of` the new inflammatory-response term, matching the issue request and literature support.\n+- `GO:0044398 venom-mediated edema` is added as `part_of` the new inflammatory-response term to satisfy the requested child relationship while preserving its established placement as a direct subtype of `venom-mediated perturbation of biological process`.\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA RESEARCH.md\nA DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,24 @@\n+## PMID:32024243 \"Inflammatory Reaction Induced by Two Metalloproteinases Isolated from Bothrops atrox Venom and by Fragments Generated from the Hydrolysis of Basement Membrane Components.\"\n+\n+Review of the abstract shows direct support for a venom-mediated inflammatory response term and for child terms capturing edema, leukocyte infiltration, and release of inflammatory mediators. The paper reports that Bothrops atrox metalloproteinases induce edema, leukocyte accumulation, and TNF-alpha release.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32024243 \"Both SVMPs induced edema, representing an increase of ~70% of the paw size. Leukocyte infiltrates reached levels of 6 × 106 with ATXL and 5 × 106 with BATXH. TNF-α was identified in the supernatant of BATXH-or venom-stimulated MPAC cells.\"\n+    - Supports venom-mediated inflammatory response as a broader parent process.\n+    - Supports venom-mediated leukocyte infiltration.\n+    - Supports venom-mediated release of inflammatory mediator.\n+\n+## PMID:19000915 \"BthMP: a new weakly hemorrhagic metalloproteinase from Bothrops moojeni snake venom.\"\n+\n+The abstract supports that a snake venom metalloproteinase contributes to inflammatory activity, edema, and leukocytic infiltrate in vivo.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:19000915 \"The edema evidenced the important role of the toxin in the inflammatory activity of the venom. BthMP also caused unclotting, and provoked histological alterations in the gastrocnemius muscle of mice inducing hemorrhage, necrosis and leukocytic infiltrate.\"\n+    - Supports venom-mediated inflammatory response.\n+    - Supports venom-mediated leukocyte infiltration.\n+\n+## PMID:26072684 \"Inflammatory mediators involved in the paw edema and hyperalgesia induced by Batroxase, a metalloproteinase isolated from Bothrops atrox snake venom.\"\n+\n+The abstract supports that inflammatory mediators, including histamine and leukotrienes, are involved in the edema response induced by venom metalloproteinase, and that mast cell degranulation contributes to this response.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26072684 \"Our results indicate a major involvement of histamine and leukotrienes in the edema and hyperalgesia induced by Batroxase, which could be related, at least in part, to mast cell degranulation.\"\n+    - Supports venom-mediated release of inflammatory mediator.\n+    - Supports adding venom-mediated mast cell degranulation as part_of venom-mediated inflammatory response.\n\nIndex: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,16 @@\n+## Relevant design-pattern review for issue #31902\n+\n+No dedicated DOSDP pattern was found for venom-mediated inflammatory outcome terms under `src/patterns`.\n+\n+Existing ontology precedent in `go-edit.obo` shows two modeling styles relevant here:\n+\n+1. Venom-mediated perturbation terms that directly regulate a host GO process often use `intersection_of` with `regulates_in_another_organism`, `positively_regulates_in_another_organism`, or `negatively_regulates_in_another_organism`.\n+2. Phenotypic or outcome-like venom terms such as `GO:0044398 venom-mediated edema`, `GO:0044521 venom-mediated muscle damage in another organism`, and `GO:0044536 venom-mediated depletion of circulating fibrinogen` are modeled more conservatively using asserted `is_a` parents and, where helpful, additional `relationship: part_of` links.\n+\n+For this issue, the conservative pattern is the better fit:\n+\n+- `venom-mediated inflammatory response` is modeled as an asserted subclass of `GO:0035738 venom-mediated perturbation of biological process`.\n+- `venom-mediated leukocyte infiltration` is modeled as an asserted subclass of the new inflammatory-response term, with an additional `part_of GO:0006954 ! inflammatory response` relationship to align it with the general inflammatory process.\n+- `venom-mediated release of inflammatory mediator` is modeled as an asserted subclass of the new inflammatory-response term without a new equivalence axiom, because \"inflammatory mediator\" spans multiple molecular entities and release processes.\n+- `GO:0044480 venom-mediated mast cell degranulation` receives `relationship: part_of` the new inflammatory-response term, matching the issue request and literature support.\n+- `GO:0044398 venom-mediated edema` is added as `part_of` the new inflammatory-response term to satisfy the requested child relationship while preserving its established placement as a direct subtype of `venom-mediated perturbation of biological process`.\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.m